                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d397">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">763.72119/2984: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Denmark</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grant-Smith</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Copenhagen</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-12-13T18:00:00+01:00"
                            >December 13, 1918—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 8:50 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3298. My 3246, December 4th, 6 p.m.<note n="12" xml:id="d397fn12">Not
                        printed.</note> Danish Minister for Foreign Affairs, under date of 12th,
                        instant,<note n="13" xml:id="d397fn13">For text of note, see <ref
                            target="#pg_457">p. 457</ref>.</note> states that the French Minister
                    has informed him that his Government had suggested that if Denmark desired to
                    have the question of the recovery of North Schleswig taken up at the Peace
                    Conference, an official request in that sense should be made to the Associated
                    Governments. M. Scavenius, therefore, makes the formal request that the Peace
                    Conference should take this matter under consideration.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grant-Smith</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
